In contrast to $N_1$, $\chi_L$ can only decay in the case of fermion DM. Being only mediated by Yukawa couplings, the decay channels of $\chi_L$ are:
\begin{eqnarray}
\chi_L\to E^-\ell^+,~N_{1,2}\nu,~\bar{N}_1\bar{N}_1,
~\bar{N}_{1}\bar{N}_{2},~\bar{N}_2\bar N_2.
\end{eqnarray}
In Fig. \ref{BRXL}, we show the branching ratios of $\chi_L$ as a function of $M_{\chi_L}$ for two sets of $\mathbb{Z}_3$ particle masses. In the low mass region, the only allowed decay is $\chi_L\to N_1\nu$. In the high mass region above $2M_{N_1}$, the decay $\chi_L\to \bar{N}_1\bar N_1$ becomes dominant. Since the mixing angle $\beta$ must be tiny in the case of fermion DM, the channels $\chi_L\to \bar N_{1}\bar N_{2},~\bar N_2\bar N_2$ are always negligible. The decay channels $\chi_L\to N_2\nu,~E^-\ell^+$ depend heavily on the mass relations between $M_{N_2}$ and $M_{N_1}$. For instance, if $M_{N_1}<M_{N_2}<2 M_{N_1}$ as in case (a), both can be the main decay channels with an approximately equal branching ratio of $\sim 0.5$ in the range between $M_{N_2}$ and $2M_{N_1}$. On the other hand, if $M_{N_2}>2 M_{N_1}$ as in case (b), neither of them dominates.

